# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: h2-database
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:h2-database/architecture] H2 implements an embedded and standalone ANSI-SQL89 compliant SQL engine on top of a B-tree based disk store.
[src:h2-database/architecture] As of October 2013, Thomas is still working on our next-generation storage engine called MVStore.
[src:h2-database/architecture] This will in time replace the B-tree based storage engine.
[src:h2-database/architecture] The parser lives in `org.h2.command.Parser`.
[src:h2-database/architecture] It uses a straightforward recursive-descent design.
[src:h2-database/architecture] See Wikipedia Recursive descent parser page.
[src:h2-database/architecture] Unlike other databases, we do not have an intermediate step where we generate some kind of IR (intermediate representation) of the query.
[src:h2-database/architecture] The parser class directly generates a command execution object.
[src:h2-database/architecture] Then we run some optimisation steps over the command to possibly generate a more efficient command.
[src:h2-database/architecture] One thing to note here is that indexes are simply stored as special kinds of tables.
[src:h2-database/architecture] We have a transaction log, which is shared among all sessions.
[src:h2-database/architecture] We also have an undo log, which is per session, to undo an operation (an update that fails for example) and to rollback a transaction.
[src:h2-database/architecture] Theoretically, the transaction log could be used, but for simplicity, H2 currently uses it's own "list of operations" (usually in-memory).
[src:h2-database/architecture] With the MVStore, this is no longer needed (just the transaction log).
[src:h2-database/architecture] The primary package of interest is `org.h2.store`.
[src:h2-database/architecture] This implements a storage mechanism which allocates pages of storage (typically 2k in size) and also implements a b-tree over those pages to allow fast retrieval and update.
[src:h2-database/architecture] The primary class of interest is `org.h2.store.FileStore`.
[src:h2-database/architecture] This implements an abstraction of a random-access file.
[src:h2-database/architecture] This allows the higher layers to treat in-memory vs. on-disk vs. zip-file databases the same.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] An **embedded database** system is a database management system (DBMS) that is tightly integrated with application software, and is embedded within the application rather than provided as a standalone system.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The term “embedded” is sometimes used to refer to use on embedded devices (as opposed to the definition given above).
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] However, only a small subset of embedded database systems are used in real-time embedded systems such as telecommunications switches and consumer electronics.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Advantage Database Server (ADS) is an embedded database management system developed by Sybase.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It provides both Indexed Sequential Access Method (ISAM) and relational data access and is compatible with multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, and Netware.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is available as a royalty-free local file-server database or as a full client-server system.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Apache Derby is an embeddable SQL database engine written entirely in Java.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is fully transactional and supports multi-user access, and is available under the Apache license.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is also distributed as part of Oracle's Java SE Development Kit (JDK) under the name of Java DB.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Empress Embedded Database was developed by Empress Software, Inc., a privately held company founded in 1979.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is a relational database management system that has been embedded in a range of applications, including medical systems, network routers, nuclear power plant monitors, and satellite management systems.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Empress is an ACID-compliant, SQL database engine with APIs for C, C++, Java, JDBC, ODBC, SQL, ADO.NET, and kernel-level APIs.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Applications developed using these APIs can be run in standalone or client-server modes.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Empress Embedded Database runs on Linux, Unix, Microsoft Windows, and real-time operating systems.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Extensible Storage Engine (ESE) is an ISAM data storage technology developed by Microsoft.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It serves as a core component of Microsoft Exchange Server and Active Directory, allowing applications to store and retrieve data using indexed and sequential access.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] ESE is also used by Windows Mail and Desktop Search in Windows Vista to store indexes and property information, respectively.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] eXtremeDB, launched by McObject LLC as an in-memory embedded database, was designed specifically for real-time embedded systems.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The initial product was later joined by eXtremeDB High Availability (HA) for fault-tolerant applications.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The eXtremeDB family now includes 64-bit and transaction logging editions, as well as the hybrid eXtremeDB Fusion, which combines in-memory and on-disk data storage.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] In 2008, McObject introduced eXtremeDB Kernel Mode, an embedded DBMS designed to run in an operating system kernel.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] eXtremeDB is used in real-time and embedded systems worldwide.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] McObject also offers Perst, an open source, object-oriented embedded database for Java, Java ME, .NET, .NET Compact Framework, and Silverlight.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded is a relational database engine and an open-source fork of InterBase.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is ACID-compliant, supports triggers and stored procedures, and is available on Linux, macOS, and Windows.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It has the same features as the Classic and SuperServer versions of Firebird.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Starting with Firebird 2.5, two or more threads or applications can access the same database simultaneously.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded acts as a local server for one-threaded client accessing its databases.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] For example, this allows ASP.NET web applications to work properly, because each user runs in a separate thread, so two users can access the same database at the same time without a conflict.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded exports the standard Firebird API entry points.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Unlike SQLite or Access databases, Firebird Embedded databases can be moved to a full Firebird server without modification and are multi-platform, running on Linux and macOS with full ASP.NET Mono support.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Although it can operate within an application process, Firebird is not truly embedded because it cannot be statically linked.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] H2 is an open-source database engine written in Java.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It supports both embedded and server modes, as well as clustering, and can run within the Google App Engine environment.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It supports encrypted database files using AES or XTEA.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Development of H2 began in May 2004, and it was first published on December 14, 2005.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] H2 is dual-licensed and is available under a modified version of the Mozilla Public License (MPL) or the unmodified Eclipse Public License (EPL) 1.0.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] HailDB is a standalone, embeddable form of the InnoDB Storage Engine.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Because it is based on the same codebase as InnoDB, it includes many of the same features, such as high performance and scalability, multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), row-level locking, deadlock detection, fault tolerance, and automatic crash recovery.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] As an embedded engine independent of MySQL, HailDB does not include server components such as networking or object-level permissions.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] By eliminating MySQL server overhead, it has a relatively small footprint and is well suited for embedding in applications that require high performance and concurrency.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] As with many embedded database systems, HailDB is designed to be accessed primarily through an ISAM-like C API rather than SQL, although a limited SQL variant is supported.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The project is no longer maintained as of 2015.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] HSQLDB is an open-source relational database management system with a BSD-like license that runs within the same Java Virtual Machine as the embedded application.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It supports a variety of in-memory and disk-based table modes, Unicode, and SQL:2016.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] InfinityDB is a sorted, hierarchical key-value store.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is available in encrypted and client-server editions.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The database provides transactional support, data compression, and operates within a single file, enabling simplified deployment and minimal administration.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] APIs include the ItemSpace interface, a ConcurrentNavigableMap view, and support for JSON.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The RemoteItemSpace component can redirect embedded API calls to other database instances.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The client-server edition includes a lightweight servlet server, web-based administration and database browsing tools, and REST support for Python.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Informix Dynamic Server (IDS) is an enterprise-class, embeddable database server that combines features such as low footprint, programmability, and autonomic capabilities with enterprise database features including high availability and flexible replication.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] IDS is used in embedded scenarios such as IP telephony call-processing systems, point-of-sale applications, and financial transaction processing systems.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] InterBase is a cross-platform, Unicode-enabled SQL database that can be embedded within turn-key applications.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It supports symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), on-disk AES-256 encryption, SQL-92 compliance, and ACID properties, and is available on Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, iOS, and Android platforms.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] InterBase is used in both small- to medium-sized and large enterprise environments, supporting multi-user and mobile application development.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] *InterBase Light* is a free version designed for mobile devices and is suitable for mobile applications.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Organizations can upgrade to a paid version as requirements for features such as change management and security increase.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] InterBase has been adopted in industries including defense, airspace, oil and gas, and manufacturing.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Kùzu is an embeddable graph database management system that supports the Cypher query language.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It implements a range of existing and novel state-of-art storage, indexing, and query processing techniques to support the management and querying of large graphs.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Kùzu achieves its performance through a combination of join algorithms, including binary and worst-case optimal joins, as well as factorization and vectorized query execution on a columnar storage layer, along with compression and parallelization techniques common in modern database systems.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Kùzu is developed and maintained by Kùzu Inc., a startup based in Waterloo, Ontario, Canada, and is available as open-source software under the MIT license.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] LevelDB is an ordered key-value store created by Google as a compact implementation of the Bigtable storage design.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is provided as a library, with a native API in C++.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It also includes official C wrappers for most functionality, and third-party wrappers are available for languages such as Python, PHP, Go, Node.js, and Objective C.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Google distributes LevelDB under the New BSD License.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Lightning Memory-Mapped Database (LMDB) is a memory-mapped key-value database developed for the OpenLDAP Project.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is written in C, and its API is modeled after the Berkeley DB API, but simplified.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The library is compact, typically compiling to under 40 KB of x86 object code.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] LMDB implements B+ trees with multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), a single-level store, copy-on-write, and provides full ACID transactions without deadlocks.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is optimized for high read concurrency: readers require no locks, readers do not block writers, and writers do not block readers, allowing read performance to scale linearly across multiple threads and CPUs.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Third-party wrappers are available for C++, Erlang and Python.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] LMDB is distributed under the OpenLDAP Public License.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] As of 2013, the OpenLDAP Project has deprecated the use of Berkeley DB in favor of LMDB.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Mimer SQL is a proprietary relational database server.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] An embedded, zero-maintenance version is available, featuring a small footprint due to its modular design, full support for the SQL standard, and ports to Windows, Linux, Automotive Grade Linux, Android, QNX, INTEGRITY, and other platforms.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] MonetDB/e is the embedded version of the open-source MonetDB SQL column store engine.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is available for C, C++, Java (JDBC), and Python, and is distributed under the MonetDB License, based on MPL 2.0.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Its predecessor, MonetDBLite (for R, Python, and Java), is no longer maintained and has been replaced by MonetDB/e.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The Embedded MySQL Server Library provides most of the features of the standard MySQL server as a linkable library that runs within the context of a client process.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] After initialization, clients can use the same C API calls as when communicating with a separate MySQL server, but with lower communication overhead and without the need for a separate database process.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] NexusDB is the commercial successor to the FlashFiler database, which is now open source.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Both databases can be embedded in Delphi applications to create stand-alone executables with full database functionality.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] ObjectDB is an object database for Java that can be used in either client-server mode or embedded (in process) mode.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Oracle's embedded database is Berkeley DB, which Oracle acquired from Sleepycat Software.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Berkeley DB was originally developed at the University of California.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is a fast, open-source embedded database and is used in several well-known open-source products, including the Linux and BSD Unix operating systems, the Apache Web server, and the OpenOffice productivity suite.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] In recent years, some projects have switched to using Lightning Memory-Mapped Database (LMDB), citing better performance in key scenarios and a simpler "less is more" design, as well as changes to Berkeley DB's licensing.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] RocksDB was created by Facebook as a fork of LevelDB.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It focuses on performance, particularly on solid-state drives (SSDs), and adds a range of features, including transactions, backups, snapshots, bloom filters, column families, expiry, custom merge operators, more tunable compaction, statistics collection, and geospatial indexing.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is used as a storage engine inside of several other databases, including ArangoDB, Ceph, CockroachDB, MyRocks, Rocksandra, TiKV, and YugabyteDB.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] solid DB is a hybrid on-disk/in-memory, relational database often used as an embedded system database in telecommunications equipment, network software, and similar applications.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] Its in-memory technology enables throughput of tens of thousands of transactions per second with response times measured in microseconds.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] A high-availability option maintains two synchronized copies of the data.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] In the event of a system failure, applications can recover access to solidDB in less than a second without data loss.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] SQLite is a software library that provides a self-contained, serverless, zero-configuration, transactional SQL database engine.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is the most widely deployed SQL database engine in the world.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The source code, written primarily in C, is in the public domain.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] SQLite includes both a native C library and a simple command-line client for managing its database.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It is included in several operating systems, including Android, FreeBSD, iOS, macOS, and Windows 10, and is also used by the Chromium web browser and its derivatives.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] SQL Server Compact is an embedded database by Microsoft with features including multi-process connections, T-SQL, ADO.NET Sync Services for synchronizing with back-end databases, Merge Replication with SQL Server, and programming APIs such as LINQ to SQL, LINQ to Entities, and ADO.NET.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] The product runs on both desktop and mobile Windows platforms.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] It has been in production software over a long period.
[src:h2-database/embedded-database] SQL Server Compact has undergone multiple rebrandings and has been known by various names, including SQL CE, SQL Server CE, SQL Server Mobile, and SQL Mobile.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] For a list of applications that work with or use H2, see: Links.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In embedded mode, an application opens a database from within the same JVM using JDBC.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This is the fastest and easiest connection mode.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The disadvantage is that a database may only be open in one virtual machine (and class loader) at any time.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] As in all modes, both persistent and in-memory databases are supported.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] There is no limit on the number of database open concurrently, or on the number of open connections.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In embedded mode I/O operations can be performed by application's threads that execute a SQL command.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The application may not interrupt these threads, it can lead to database corruption, because JVM closes I/O handle during thread interruption.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Consider other ways to control execution of your application.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When interrupts are possible the `async:` file system can be used as a workaround, but full safety is not guaranteed.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] It's recommended to use the client-server model instead, the client side may interrupt own threads.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When using the server mode (sometimes called remote mode or client/server mode), an application opens a database remotely using the JDBC or ODBC API.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] A server needs to be started within the same or another virtual machine, or on another computer.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Many applications can connect to the same database at the same time, by connecting to this server.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Internally, the server process opens the database(s) in embedded mode.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The server mode is slower than the embedded mode, because all data is transferred over TCP/IP.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] There is no limit on the number of database open concurrently per server, or on the number of open connections.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The mixed mode is a combination of the embedded and the server mode.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The first application that connects to a database does that in embedded mode, but also starts a server so that other applications (running in different processes or virtual machines) can concurrently access the same data.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The local connections are as fast as if the database is used in just the embedded mode, while the remote connections are a bit slower.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The server can be started and stopped from within the application (using the server API), or automatically (automatic mixed mode).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When using the automatic mixed mode, all clients that want to connect to the database (no matter if it's an local or remote connection) can do so using the exact same database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This database supports multiple connection modes and connection settings.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This is achieved using different database URLs.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Settings in the URLs are not case sensitive.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The database URL for connecting to a local database is `jdbc:h2:[file:][<path>]<databaseName>`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If no or only a relative path is used, then the current working directory is used as a starting point.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The case sensitivity of the path and database name depend on the operating system, however it is recommended to use lowercase letters only.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The database name must be at least three characters long (a limitation of `File.createTempFile`).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The database name must not contain a semicolon.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To point to the user home directory, use `~/`, as in: `jdbc:h2:~/test`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] For certain use cases (for example: rapid prototyping, testing, high performance operations, read-only databases), it may not be required to persist data, or persist changes to the data.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This database supports the in-memory mode, where the data is not persisted.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In some cases, only one connection to a in-memory database is required.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This means the database to be opened is private.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In this case, the database URL is `jdbc:h2:mem:` Opening two connections within the same virtual machine means opening two different (private) databases.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Sometimes multiple connections to the same in-memory database are required.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In this case, the database URL must include a name.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Accessing the same database using this URL only works within the same virtual machine and class loader environment.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To access an in-memory database from another process or from another computer, you need to start a TCP server in the same process as the in-memory database was created.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The other processes then need to access the database over TCP/IP or TLS, using a database URL such as: `jdbc:h2:tcp://localhost/mem:db1`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] By default, closing the last connection to a database closes the database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] For an in-memory database, this means the content is lost.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To keep the database open, add `;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1` to the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To keep the content of an in-memory database as long as the virtual machine is alive, use `jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This may create a memory leak, when you need to remove the database, use the SHUTDOWN command.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use file encryption, you need to specify the encryption algorithm (the 'cipher') and the file password (in addition to the user password) when connecting to the database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] By default, a new database is automatically created if it does not exist yet when the embedded url is used.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To create an encrypted database, connect to it as it would already exist locally using the embedded URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The encryption algorithm is set in the database URL, and the file password is specified in the password field, before the user password.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] A single space separates the file password and the user password; the file password itself may not contain spaces.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] File passwords and user passwords are case sensitive.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To encrypt an existing database, use the `ChangeFileEncryption` tool.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This tool can also decrypt an encrypted database, or change the file encryption key.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The tool is available from within the H2 Console in the tools section, or you can run it from the command line.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Whenever a database is opened, a lock file is created to signal other processes that the database is in use.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If database is closed, or if the process that opened the database terminates, this lock file is deleted.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To open the database with a different file locking method, use the parameter `FILE_LOCK`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] For more information about the algorithms, see Advanced / File Locking Protocols.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] By default, when an application calls `DriverManager.getConnection(url, ...)` with embedded URL and the database specified in the URL does not yet exist, a new (empty) database is created.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In some situations, it is better to restrict creating new databases, and only allow to open existing databases.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To do this, add `;IFEXISTS=TRUE` to the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In this case, if the database does not already exist, an exception is thrown when trying to connect.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The connection only succeeds when the database already exists.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Usually, a database is closed when the last connection to it is closed.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In some situations this slows down the application, for example when it is not possible to keep at least one connection open.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The automatic closing of a database can be delayed or disabled with the SQL statement `SET DB_CLOSE_DELAY <seconds>`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The parameter <seconds> specifies the number of seconds to keep a database open after the last connection to it was closed.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The value -1 means the database is not closed automatically.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The value 0 is the default and means the database is closed when the last connection is closed.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This setting is persistent and can be set by an administrator only.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] It is possible to set the value in the database URL: `jdbc:h2:~/test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=10`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] By default, a database is closed when the last connection is closed.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] However, if it is never closed, a persistent database is closed when the virtual machine exits normally, using a shutdown hook.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In some situations, the database should not be closed in this case, for example because the database is still used at virtual machine shutdown (to store the shutdown process in the database for example).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] For those cases, the automatic closing of the database can be disabled in the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The first connection (the one that is opening the database) needs to set the option in the database URL (it is not possible to change the setting afterwards).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] command by itself in its own shutdown hook after completion of all operations with database to avoid data loss and should not try to establish new connections to database after that.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Sometimes, particularly for in-memory databases, it is useful to be able to execute DDL or DML commands automatically when a client connects to a database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This functionality is enabled via the INIT property.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Note that multiple commands may be passed to INIT, but the semicolon delimiter must be escaped, as in the example below.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Please note the double backslash is only required in a Java or properties file.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Backslashes within the init script (for example within a runscript statement, to specify the folder names in Windows) need to be escaped as well (using a second backslash).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] It might be simpler to avoid backslashes in folder names for this reason; use forward slashes instead.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Some applications (for example OpenOffice.org Base) pass some additional parameters when connecting to the database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Why those parameters are passed is unknown.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The parameters `PREFERDOSLIKELINEENDS` and `IGNOREDRIVERPRIVILEGES` are such examples; they are simply ignored to improve the compatibility with OpenOffice.org.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If an application passes other parameters when connecting to the database, usually the database throws an exception saying the parameter is not supported.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] It is possible to ignored such parameters by adding `;IGNORE_UNKNOWN_SETTINGS=TRUE` to the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In addition to the settings already described, other database settings can be passed in the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Adding `;setting=value` at the end of a database URL is the same as executing the statement `SET setting value` just after connecting.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] For a list of supported settings, see SQL Grammar or the DbSettings javadoc.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Usually, the database opens the database file with the access mode `rw`, meaning read-write (except for read only databases, where the mode `r` is used).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To open a database in read-only mode if the database file is not read-only, use `ACCESS_MODE_DATA=r`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] For more information see Durability Problems.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] On many operating systems the access mode `rws` does not guarantee that the data is written to the disk.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] An application can open multiple databases at the same time, including multiple connections to the same database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The number of open database is only limited by the memory available.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If you want to access the same database at the same time from different processes or computers, you need to use the client / server mode.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In this case, one process acts as the server, and the other processes (that could reside on other computers as well) connect to the server via TCP/IP (or TLS over TCP/IP for improved security).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If an application is multi-threaded, it does not need to worry about synchronizing access to the database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] An application should normally use one connection per thread.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This database synchronizes access to the same connection, but other databases may not do this.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To get higher concurrency, you need to use multiple connections.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] An application can use multiple threads that access the same database at the same time.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Threads that use different connections can use the database concurrently.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Usually, `SELECT` statements will generate read locks.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Statements that modify data use write locks on the modified rows.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] It is also possible to issue write locks without modifying data, using the statement `SELECT ...
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Data definition statements may issue exclusive locks on tables.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The statements `COMMIT` and `ROLLBACK` releases all open locks.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The commands `SAVEPOINT` and `ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT` don't affect locks.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The locks are also released when the autocommit mode changes, and for connections with autocommit set to true (this is the default), locks are released after each statement.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The number of seconds until a lock timeout exception is thrown can be set separately for each connection using the SQL command `SET LOCK_TIMEOUT <milliseconds>`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The initial lock timeout (that is the timeout used for new connections) can be set using the SQL command `SET DEFAULT_LOCK_TIMEOUT <milliseconds>`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Database name and location are not stored inside the database files.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] While a database is closed, the files can be moved to another directory, and they can be renamed as well (as long as all files of the same database start with the same name and the respective extensions are unchanged).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] As there is no platform specific data in the files, they can be moved to other operating systems without problems.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When the database is closed, it is possible to backup the database files.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To backup data while the database is running, the SQL commands `SCRIPT` and `BACKUP` can be used.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Whenever data is modified in the database and those changes are committed, the changes are written to the transaction log (except for in-memory objects).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The changes to the main data area itself are usually written later on, to optimize disk access.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If there is a power failure, the main data area is not up-to-date, but because the changes are in the transaction log, the next time the database is opened, the changes are re-applied automatically.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] All database engines behave a little bit different.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Where possible, H2 supports the ANSI SQL standard, and tries to be compatible to other databases.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In MySQL text columns are case insensitive by default, while in H2 they are case sensitive.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] However H2 supports case insensitive columns as well.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To create the tables with case insensitive texts, append `IGNORECASE=TRUE` to the database URL (example: `jdbc:h2:~/test;IGNORECASE=TRUE`).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] For certain features, this database can emulate the behavior of specific databases.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] However, only a small subset of the differences between databases are implemented in this way.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the STRICT mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=STRICT` or the SQL statement `SET MODE STRICT`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In this mode some deprecated features are disabled.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If your application or library uses only the H2 or it generates different SQL for different database systems it is recommended to use this compatibility mode in unit tests to reduce possibility of accidental misuse of such features.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This mode cannot be used as SQL validator, however.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] It is not recommended to enable this mode in production builds of libraries, because this mode may become more restrictive in future releases of H2 that may break your library if it will be used together with newer version of H2.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the LEGACY mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=LEGACY` or the SQL statement `SET MODE LEGACY`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In this mode some compatibility features for applications written for H2 1.X are enabled.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This mode doesn't provide full compatibility with H2 1.X.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the IBM DB2 mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=DB2;DEFAULT_NULL_ORDERING=HIGH` or the SQL statement `SET MODE DB2`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the Apache Derby mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=Derby;DEFAULT_NULL_ORDERING=HIGH` or the SQL statement `SET MODE Derby`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the HSQLDB mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=HSQLDB;DEFAULT_NULL_ORDERING=FIRST` or the SQL statement `SET MODE HSQLDB`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the MS SQL Server mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=MSSQLServer;DATABASE_TO_UPPER=FALSE;CASE_INSENSITIVE_IDENTIFIERS=TRUE`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Do not change value of DATABASE_TO_LOWER and CASE_INSENSITIVE_IDENTIFIERS after creation of database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the MariaDB mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=MariaDB;DATABASE_TO_LOWER=TRUE`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When case-insensitive identifiers are needed append `;CASE_INSENSITIVE_IDENTIFIERS=TRUE` to URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Do not change value of DATABASE_TO_LOWER after creation of database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Text comparison in MariaDB is case insensitive by default, while in H2 it is case sensitive (as in most other databases).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] H2 does support case insensitive text comparison, but it needs to be set separately, using `SET IGNORECASE TRUE`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This affects comparison using `=, LIKE, REGEXP`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the MySQL mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=MySQL;DATABASE_TO_LOWER=TRUE`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Text comparison in MySQL is case insensitive by default, while in H2 it is case sensitive (as in most other databases).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the Oracle mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=Oracle;DEFAULT_NULL_ORDERING=HIGH` or the SQL statement `SET MODE Oracle`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use the PostgreSQL mode, use the database URL `jdbc:h2:~/test;MODE=PostgreSQL;DATABASE_TO_LOWER=TRUE;DEFAULT_NULL_ORDERING=HIGH`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The auto-reconnect feature causes the JDBC driver to reconnect to the database if the connection is lost.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The automatic re-connect only occurs when auto-commit is enabled; if auto-commit is disabled, an exception is thrown.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To enable this mode, append `;AUTO_RECONNECT=TRUE` to the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] After an automatic re-connect, variables and local temporary tables definitions (excluding data) are re-created.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The contents of the system table `INFORMATION_SCHEMA.SESSION_STATE` contains all client side state that is re-created.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If another connection uses the database in exclusive mode (enabled using `SET EXCLUSIVE 1` or `SET EXCLUSIVE 2`), then this connection will try to re-connect until the exclusive mode ends.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Multiple processes can access the same database without having to start the server manually.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To do that, append `;AUTO_SERVER=TRUE` to the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] You can use the same database URL independent of whether the database is already open or not.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This feature doesn't work with in-memory databases.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Use the same URL for all connections to this database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Internally, when using this mode, the first connection to the database is made in embedded mode, and additionally a server is started internally (as a daemon thread).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If the database is already open in another process, the server mode is used automatically.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The IP address and port of the server are stored in the file `.lock.db`, that's why in-memory databases can't be supported.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The application that opens the first connection to the database uses the embedded mode, which is faster than the server mode.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Therefore the main application should open the database first if possible.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The first connection automatically starts a server on a random port.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This server allows remote connections, however only to this database (to ensure that, the client reads `.lock.db` file and sends the random key that is stored there to the server).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When the first connection is closed, the server stops.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If other (remote) connections are still open, one of them will then start a server (auto-reconnect is enabled automatically).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] All processes need to have access to the database files.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If the first connection is closed (the connection that started the server), open transactions of other connections will be rolled back (this may not be a problem if you don't disable autocommit).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Explicit client/server connections (using `jdbc:h2:tcp://` or `ssl://`) are not supported.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This mode is not supported for in-memory databases.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Here is an example how to use this mode.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Application 1 and 2 are not necessarily started on the same computer, but they need to have access to the database files.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Application 1 and 2 are typically two different processes (however they could run within the same process).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When using this feature, by default the server uses any free TCP port.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The port can be set manually using `AUTO_SERVER_PORT=9090`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The page size for new databases is 4 KiB (4096 bytes), unless the page size is set explicitly in the database URL using `PAGE_SIZE=` when the database is created.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The page size of existing databases can not be changed, so this property needs to be set when the database is created.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The page size of encrypted databases must be a multiple of 4096 (4096, 8192, …).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To find problems in an application, it is sometimes good to see what database operations where executed.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The simplest way to enable the trace option is setting it in the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] There are two settings, one for `System.out` (`TRACE_LEVEL_SYSTEM_OUT`) tracing, and one for file tracing (`TRACE_LEVEL_FILE`).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The trace levels are 0 for `OFF`, 1 for `ERROR` (the default), 2 for `INFO`, and 3 for `DEBUG`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The trace level can be changed at runtime by executing the SQL command `SET TRACE_LEVEL_SYSTEM_OUT level` (for `System.out` tracing) or `SET TRACE_LEVEL_FILE level` (for file tracing).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When using a high trace level, the trace file can get very big quickly.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The default size limit is 16 MB, if the trace file exceeds this limit, it is renamed to `.old` and a new file is created.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If another such file exists, it is deleted.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To limit the size to a certain number of megabytes, use `SET TRACE_MAX_FILE_SIZE mb`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When setting the trace level to `INFO` or `DEBUG`, Java source code is generated as well.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The generated file `Test.java` will contain the Java source code.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The generated source code may be too large to compile (the size of a Java method is limited).
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If this is the case, the source code needs to be split in multiple methods.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] The password is not listed in the trace file and therefore not included in the source code.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] By default, this database uses its own native 'trace' facility.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] This facility is called 'trace' and not 'log' within this database to avoid confusion with the transaction log.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Trace messages can be written to both file and `System.out`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] In most cases, this is sufficient, however sometimes it is better to use the same facility as the application, for example Log4j.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To do that, this database support SLF4J.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] SLF4J is a simple facade for various logging APIs and allows to plug in the desired implementation at deployment time.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] SLF4J supports implementations such as Logback, Log4j, Jakarta Commons Logging (JCL), Java logging, x4juli, and Simple Log.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Changing the log mechanism is not possible after the database is open, that means executing the SQL statement `SET TRACE_LEVEL_FILE 4` when the database is already open will not have the desired effect.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To use SLF4J, all required jar files need to be in the classpath.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If it does not work, check the file `<database>.trace.db` for error messages.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] If the database files are read-only, then the database is read-only as well.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] It is not possible to create new tables, add or modify data in this database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Only `SELECT` and `CALL` statements are allowed.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] To create a read-only database, close the database.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] When you open the database now, it is read-only.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] There are two ways an application can find out whether database is read-only: by calling `Connection.isReadOnly()` or by executing the SQL statement `CALL READONLY()`.
[src:h2-database/features-p01] Using the Custom Access Mode `r` the database can also be opened in read-only mode, even if the database file is not read only.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] To create a read-only database in a zip file, first create a regular persistent database, and then create a backup.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The database must not have pending changes, that means you need to close all connections to the database first.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] To speed up opening the read-only database and running queries, the database should be closed using `SHUTDOWN DEFRAG`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If you are using a database named `test`, an easy way to create a zip file is using the `Backup` tool.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] You can start the tool from the command line, or from within the H2 Console (Tools - Backup).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Please note that the database must be closed when the backup is created.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Therefore, the SQL statement `BACKUP TO` can not be used.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The performance for some queries will be slower than when using a regular database, because random access in zip files is not supported (only streaming).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] How much this affects the performance depends on the queries and the data.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The database is not read in memory; therefore large databases are supported as well.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The same indexes are used as when using a regular database.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If the database is larger than a few megabytes, performance is much better if the database file is split into multiple smaller files, because random access in compressed files is not possible.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] See also the sample application ReadOnlyDatabaseInZip.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If a database cannot be opened because the boot info (the SQL script that is run at startup) is corrupted, then the database can be opened by specifying a database event listener.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The exceptions are logged, but opening the database will continue.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Each column is either a base column or a generated column.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] A generated column is a column whose value is calculated before storing and cannot be assigned directly.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The formula is evaluated when the row is inserted, and re-evaluated every time the row is updated.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Function indexes are not directly supported by this database, but they can be emulated by using generated columns.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] When inserting data, it is not required (and not allowed) to specify a value for the upper-case version of the column, because the value is generated.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] A tool is provided to execute efficient multi-dimension (spatial) range queries.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] This database does not support a specialized spatial index (R-Tree or similar).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] For each record, the multi-dimensional key is converted (mapped) to a single dimensional (scalar) value.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] This value specifies the location on a space-filling curve.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Currently, Z-order (also called N-order or Morton-order) is used; Hilbert curve could also be used, but the implementation is more complex.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The algorithm to convert the multi-dimensional value is called bit-interleaving.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The scalar value is indexed using a B-Tree index (usually using a generated column).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The method can result in a drastic performance improvement over just using an index on the first column.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Depending on the data and number of dimensions, the improvement is usually higher than factor 5.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The tool generates a SQL query from a specified multi-dimensional range.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The method used is not database dependent, and the tool can easily be ported to other databases.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] For an example how to use the tool, please have a look at the sample code provided in `TestMultiDimension.java`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] In addition to the built-in functions, this database supports user-defined Java functions.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] In this database, Java functions can be used as stored procedures as well.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] A function must be declared (registered) before it can be used.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] A function can be defined using source code, or as a reference to a compiled class that is available in the classpath.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] By default, the function aliases are stored in the current schema.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] When referencing a method, the class must already be compiled and included in the classpath where the database is running.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Only static Java methods are supported; both the class and the method must be public.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The Java function must be registered in the database by calling `CREATE ALIAS ...
[src:h2-database/features-p02] For a complete sample application, see `src/test/org/h2/samples/Function.java`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] When defining a function alias with source code, the database tries to compile the source code using the Java compiler (the class `javax.tool.ToolProvider.getSystemJavaCompiler()`) if it is in the classpath.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If not, `javac` is run as a separate process.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Only the source code is stored in the database; the class is compiled each time the database is re-opened.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Source code can be passed as dollar quoted text (`$$source code$$`) to avoid escaping problems.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If you use some third-party script processing tool, use standard single quotes instead and don't forget to repeat each single quotation mark twice within the source code.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] By default, the three packages `java.util, java.math, java.sql` are imported.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The method name (`nextPrime` in the example above) is ignored.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Method overloading is not supported when declaring functions as source code, that means only one method may be declared for an alias.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Multiple methods may be bound to a SQL function if the class is already compiled and included in the classpath.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Each Java method must have a different number of arguments.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Method overloading is not supported when declaring functions as source code.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Functions that accept non-nullable parameters such as `int` will not be called if one of those parameters is `NULL`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Instead, the result of the function is `NULL`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If the function should be called if a parameter is `NULL`, you need to use `java.lang.Integer` instead.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] SQL types are mapped to Java classes and vice-versa as in the JDBC API.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] There are a few special cases: `java.lang.Object` is mapped to `OTHER` (a serialized object).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Therefore, `java.lang.Object` can not be used to match all SQL types (matching all SQL types is not supported).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The second special case is `Object[]`: arrays of any class are mapped to `ARRAY`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Objects of type `org.h2.value.Value` (the internal value class) are passed through without conversion.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If the first parameter of a Java function is a `java.sql.Connection`, then the connection to database is provided.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] This connection does not need to be closed before returning.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] When calling the method from within the SQL statement, this connection parameter does not need to be (can not be) specified.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If a function throws an exception, then the current statement is rolled back and the exception is thrown to the application.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] SQLException are directly re-thrown to the calling application; all other exceptions are first converted to a SQLException.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] A function that returns a result set can be used like a table.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] However, in this case the function is called at least twice: first while parsing the statement to collect the column names (with parameters set to `null` where not known at compile time).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] And then, while executing the statement to get the data (maybe multiple times if this is a join).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If the function is called just to get the column list, the URL of the connection passed to the function is `jdbc:columnlist:connection`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Otherwise, the URL of the connection is `jdbc:default:connection`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] For situations where you need to expose other data-sources to the SQL engine as a table, there are "pluggable tables".
[src:h2-database/features-p02] For some examples, have a look at the code in `org.h2.test.db.TestTableEngines`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] In which case the parameters are passed down in the tableEngineParams field of the CreateTableData object.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Params from the schema are used when CREATE TABLE issued on this schema does not have its own engine params specified.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] This database supports Java triggers that are called before or after a row is updated, inserted or deleted.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Triggers can be used for complex consistency checks, or to update related data in the database.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] It is also possible to use triggers to simulate materialized views.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] For a complete sample application, see `src/test/org/h2/samples/TriggerSample.java`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] A Java trigger must implement the interface `org.h2.api.Trigger`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The trigger class must be available in the classpath of the database engine (when using the server mode, it must be in the classpath of the server).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The connection can be used to query or update data in other tables.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The trigger can be used to veto a change by throwing a `SQLException`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] As an alternative to implementing the `Trigger` interface, an application can extend the abstract class `org.h2.tools.TriggerAdapter`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] This will allows to use the `ResultSet` interface within trigger implementations.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Empty space in the database file re-used automatically.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] When closing the database, the database is automatically compacted for up to 200 milliseconds by default.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] To compact more, use the SQL statement SHUTDOWN COMPACT.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] However re-creating the database may further reduce the database size because this will re-build the indexes.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] See also the sample application `org.h2.samples.Compact`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The commands `SCRIPT / RUNSCRIPT` can be used as well to create a backup of a database and re-build the database from the script.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The database keeps most frequently used data in the main memory.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The amount of memory used for caching can be changed using the setting `CACHE_SIZE`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] This setting can be set in the database connection URL (`jdbc:h2:~/test;CACHE_SIZE=131072`), or it can be changed at runtime using `SET CACHE_SIZE size`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The size of the cache, as represented by `CACHE_SIZE` is measured in KB, with each KB being 1024 bytes.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] This setting has no effect for in-memory databases.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] For persistent databases, the setting is stored in the database and re-used when the database is opened the next time.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] However, when opening an existing database, the cache size is set to at most half the amount of memory available for the virtual machine (Runtime.getRuntime().maxMemory()), even if the cache size setting stored in the database is larger; however the setting stored in the database is kept.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Setting the cache size in the database URL or explicitly using `SET CACHE_SIZE` overrides this value (even if larger than the physical memory).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] An experimental scan-resistant cache algorithm "Two Queue" (2Q) is available.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] To enable it, append `;CACHE_TYPE=TQ` to the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The cache might not actually improve performance.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] If you plan to use it, please run your own test cases first.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Also included is an experimental second level soft reference cache.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Rows in this cache are only garbage collected on low memory.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] By default the second level cache is disabled.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] To get information about page reads and writes, and the current caching algorithm in use, call `SELECT * FROM INFORMATION_SCHEMA.SETTINGS`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] The number of pages read / written is listed.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] External authentication allows to optionally validate user credentials externally (JAAS,LDAP,custom classes).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Is also possible to temporary assign roles to externally authenticated users.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] To enable external authentication on a database execute statement `SET AUTHENTICATOR TRUE`.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] This setting in persisted on the database.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] To connect on a database by using external credentials client must append `AUTHREALM=H2` to the database URL.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] `H2` is the identifier of the authentication realm (see later).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] External authentication requires to send password to the server.
[src:h2-database/features-p02] By default external authentication is performed through JAAS login interface (configuration name is `h2`).
[src:h2-database/features-p02] Is it possible to specify custom authentication settings by using JVM argument `-Dh2auth.configurationFile={urlOfH2Auth.xml}`.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The software is available as open source software Mozilla Public License 2.0 or the original Eclipse Public License.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The development of the H2 database engine started in May 2004, and first published in December 2005.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The database engine was written by Thomas Mueller.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] He also developed the Java database engine Hypersonic SQL.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] In 2001, the Hypersonic SQL project was stopped, and the HSQLDB Group was formed to continue work on the Hypersonic SQL code.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The name H2 stands for Hypersonic 2, however H2 does not share code with Hypersonic SQL or HSQLDB.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] Version 2.0.x was released in January 2022.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] A subset of the SQL (Structured Query Language) standard is supported.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The main programming APIs are SQL and JDBC, however the database also supports using the PostgreSQL ODBC driver by acting like a PostgreSQL server.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] It is possible to create both in-memory tables, as well as disk-based tables.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] Index types are hash table and tree for in-memory tables, and b-tree for disk-based tables.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] All data manipulation operations are transactional.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] Table level locking and multiversion concurrency control are implemented.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The two-phase commit protocol is supported as well, but no standard API for distributed transactions is implemented.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The security features of the database are: role based access rights, encryption of the password using SHA-256 and data using the AES or the Tiny Encryption Algorithm, XTEA.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The cryptographic features are available as functions inside the database as well.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] SSL / TLS connections are supported in the client–server mode, as well as when using the console application.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] The database supports protection against SQL injection by enforcing the use of parameterized statements.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] In H2, this feature is called 'disabling literals'.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] Two full text search implementations are included, a native implementation and one using Lucene.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] A simple form of high availability is implemented: when used in the client–server mode, the database engine supports hot failover (this is commonly known as clustering).
[src:h2-database/h2-database] However, the clustering mode must be enabled manually after a failure.
[src:h2-database/h2-database] Since version 1.1.111, H2 in-memory database can run inside the Google App Engine.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:h2-database/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:h2-database/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
